        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Conviviality is the name of a gathering. I built a table of clay and wood, surrounding it with eight plates, cups and a bowl. Gourmet Subdued is about the forms that the gathering leaves behind. Food and drink are gone; the table and its iterations are left to delay and refine what have been consumed. The work is a celebration of the moment, the implication of what was consumed puts the aftertaste in the mouth. So life and art have many shades of meaning. I take inspiration from a high white mountain pass in the Monashee Mountains of central British Columbia. Occasional gatherings on the edge of a remote pass between the Pacific and Cariboo Valleys; it has been welcoming immigrants since the gold rush. The table will be waiting on the bench at that quiet location waiting for return conviviality.
