        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        A china pot is nothing but clay with a hole. A glass is nothing but a metal with a hole, simple as that. And it's the not the inside nothing hole, but the not the outside nothing hole. This "nothing", even if it depends on what you call, is the hole of everything, the truth, the rationality, the spirit, the fantasy, the absense, the mind, the ink, the water, the colour of all colour, the nothing with all the possibilities, the condition for every space/time, without condition. Therefore, the Middle Ages defined God simply as "OH" (as in "Big O"), which stands for Not a Thing. To make "O" possible, these holes had to be filled with simple materials to permute, transmutate and transmit the vibe to all kinds of phenomenons, in our present and in other planets. The Reality of a simpler vessel means to transmit an endorphinity, a first gnosis or inner spirit, so little that the body will be aware from that emptiness, the body can fill it, but not swallow it. Being an artist, I’m more interested about the awe of these spirits in the hole in the first place, and of the holes themselves, inseparable from the statics and dynamics, architecture and cosmology, or meta-physics and astrophysics. Over history, the holes have been here with us in a lapidary, animated way, so little that if one passes through them, he can be "plugged into" the energy of all the spirit persons that have gone before, after, and are possible."
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        "The artist has attained the highest plane of self actualization and the complete epitome of human potential. In the eye of the creative mind, no new configurations are to appear. It has become dull and insensitive to stimulation from within or without. The mot juste alone may be extracted from the dullard awareness. The creative mind requires total void. The peripheral senses remain the sole channels of information outside the subconscious. The foundation of the creative essence is a perpetual dichotomy between the actual and the conceivable. The entire nature of creativity consists of the primordial oscillation between the possible and impossible." Raymond N. Vezina
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        My practice currently treats the dichotomy between ephemerality and containment – between the imponderable and the highly sculptural – between the intangible and the tactile. My work at any given moment of conceptualization is highly concerned with how the mind mediates between pure abstraction and surface description. What happens in the minds eye when confronted with visual phenomena, I’m interested in the phenomenon and in how the viewer interacts with it. Unlike the great analytical sculptors who work in three dimensions, I use wood, clay, concrete and my own body as source material to make modular sculptures and installations using a non-hierarchical methodology. The system of connections that are made between the pieces determines the space of the construction. The intentional incompleteness of the sculpture is an ever-changing, tactile experience of concrete shapes and spaces. Their work is derived from processes that creates objects and installations the outcomes are partly informed by social interactions and partly independent of them.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        The level of craft and the amount of individuality and expression varies depending on what kind of pot an artist is making. I see two distinct differences: utility vs. decorative. Throughout history and in many cultures, vessels have carried many functions from ritual ceremony to cooking. Aesthetically these vessels are usually more restrained than their purely decorative counterparts; however, this does not mean they have less artistry. These utilitarian pots provide a context of their own. I am under the strong influence of earth, material, and familiarity – habitual behavior of some kind. Food is consumed here, moments are cherished here, in a quiet way it provides the stability and foundation of our being.
        This balance of familiar comfort and anxiety is an aesthetic I strive to achieve in all of my work.
        This body of work changes my ideas with repetition as much as being in their presence relaxes me. 
        When pressed for a pots genesis and purpose, one can’t produce any explanation beyond the presence of erosion. Rivers carve away, cutting their ever-spiraling paths, shaping the world beneath them since the beginning of time, eroding sediment deposited by Ice Age glaciers. Their path is as much a journey of the spirit as the physical travel of water across the land. I want to be present in that narrative, to give physical presence to something I have spent my whole life dreaming about. 
        Continued experimentation over the years has allowed me to envision a whole body of work continuing the current theme. 
        </p>
        <p>
        didn’t have a goal, I just sat down and did it. A few years later hundreds of pots lie on my shelves, inviting viewers to take them up and wander what they mean.
        </p>
        <p>
        I am totally obsessed with finding new, powerful and provocative ways to interact with landscape through animals, rocks, mountains, rivers, fields and forests. To me this is a whole body of work that continues to grow – breathing in and out of this same obsession.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Doing the same thing over and over again every day. I “see” it in my mind first then create it – thousands and millions of times. Not bored with the work… completely involved in exploring the process.
        Producing idea after idea always testing the parameters of the medium. A push/pull between limiting forms, process and materials and the opposite – to be unlimited by my own ability.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Pots mimic the art of conversation. When they gather together in a room it feels like they are engaged in a discussion, poised in negotiation with one another. Each moving back and forth in a way that suggests neither lead nor obeys the other. Their ambiguity reassures viewers that interpretation of their gestures is dependent on viewing context as much as sight. 
        </p>
        <p>
        The pieced-together aesthetic refers to the phenomenon of steel migratory work. Instead of people moving from city to city to find work, steel workers would often be laid off and move their families to another region where there was a steel mill. They would sometimes be laid off and move factories for more work, often settling in a different town where they would buy a house where they no longer needed to rent. This migratory work practice is formally related to how the pieces are put together in our traditional coiling unfired vessel, using whatever materials we have available to us, in the location where we are living and working, then with the aid of a kiln, fuse them together.
        </p>
        <p>
        We have moved quite a few times and for much of the work in this body I was making pots, staying somewhere for just a few months at a time. I move a lot and the pots I make become works on migration.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        There are 3 Visions of relief, 3 dimensions happening simultaneously with every stroke. One is the beginning, first stroke on the clay, a mental sketch, an abstraction, beyond words, like longing to connect, to touch, to enter into. The 2nd is how I clean up, or take away material to set relief visual elements into 2 dimension space while holding the space in relief. The 3rd, after the pot is bisque fired, I size and glaze the surface. The 3rd dimension is endless how I use the surface coloring and textures to inform the pot, emphasize a feeling, set light into the space, it’s texture and scale. As if it was a place, setting the stage, using color on the walls and ceiling to set a feeling. Think theater as in sculpture, not community theatre.
        </p>
        <p>
        Secrets are hidden in the relief, colors hide tension and hold the other areas in focus.
        The color accents and sets accents into the rhythm of the relief planes, visual/aesthetic and sensory.
        Areas of stress are revealed, maybe awkwardly placed, the backbone? Relief highlights and attracts a viewers unconscious. It’s light and free, kinesthetic, active and a kinetic feel.
        Work is significantly layered. The layers of activity, the spilling over helps hold each area in relief. Visual travel from one side to the other side fuels the interest in pots as sculptural objects. Some pieces will stay whole in front of you while others really need to be spun in order to be read – turning away from the image to introspect, decipher, process. Looks can be deceiving. Starts are slow, having a difficult time beginning.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Presenting work, showing 1-5 pots at a time is a concept idea that I feel helps me show my ability to manipulate different glazes and placement of them, depth of firing and color contrasts since I commonly associate my work with puppetry.
        </p>
        <p>
        It’s not the piece alone but the amazing space they recreate visually. I have a puppet background, so I manipulate my pieces like a show.
        </p>
        <p>
        I manipulate my pieces to signify space and place where they occupy, the ability to climb in and enjoy on a regular basis.
        </p>
        <p>
        The mystery of my pieces starts with the dark base construction, the mystery of having to discover the anomalies, what are they? They are always performing like a show of controlled chaos. My suggestion is the design of the piece is suggesting multiple ideas but at this time I am not giving up all secrets of my pieces.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Silicon, aluminum, and magnesium, elements known most commonly for their reciprocal roles as conductors, transitional metals, and vital ions in an array of organisms’ bio-chemical exchanges, have historically provided the fine potter with fluid vessels of varying degrees of conductivity and compressibility. Modern methodologies of the potter's wheel can be traced back to pre-modern cultures and technologies, which relied on prehistoric clay-lined fermentation pots and bread ovens to concoct silica material.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        The sequential process of clay innovation is restricted to a moderate analog, but what technology has submitted in speed, flexibility, and efficiency, has in turn offered an amplified spectrum of compositional options. Sampling effects of electric currents, arching temperatures in oxidation, and yet greater transparency in firing speed - all in time and stillness - are in fact our liberties. Much like the dilemma of modern man, to predictably govern or naturally grope for control, it is insight through the colorless lens of perspective that mirrors a near century of electric spark.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Working from a tradition, derived from American studio craft pottery of the 1950s-1960s, my pots deliver a familiarity of form, material, and surface manipulations. Each piece is an investigation into singular construction techniques. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Single pieces are inspired by current events, memories, social meditations, geological data, museum experiences, family secrets, pop music, folk culture and other ephemera. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        My utilitarian salt and pepper shakers exemplify how in a self-perpetuating, cyclical nature pottery can monitor and influence functional objects. By altering the scale of appropriate production methods and focusing on the intrasnse quality of hand made I alter the context of ceramics in our daily lives. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I am interested in how my individual choice of materials leads to effects that can be explored and, to some extent, predicted.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        For the past several years I have searched for ways to compose forms, volumes, and surface qualities into an emotional and intellectually coherent response. Many works that look like round bowls start out as square pieces of clay, others as a tunnel of clay, pressed out under my feet while standing on a sculptural form. These accidental forms are stored in my memory.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I make decisions about what to discard or repair based on an intuitive desire to move a work through to completion. I am attracted to the impermanence of a material that also has a memory of its history, making studio work a unique opportunity to allow accidental forms, happy accidents, and planned events to accumulate into a type of storytelling, each piece providing a narrative of my time here on earth. Due to this accumulation, no two pots are alike, when they keep their memory. They all have an aura, and with each additional firing over time, the aura changes.
        </p>
        <p>
        My research into the properties of clay and glazes has been ongoing for the past 25 or so years using cement, fabric, glass beads, found objects, wood, paper, plastic, and naturally occurring objects to alter the surfaces of my pots.
        </p>
        <p>
        To create two- and three-dimensional works, depending on the interests of the project, I apply wood and gypsum board, using glues, screws, nails, water jets, brackets, and threaded rods. I continue working on my wheel from time to time. To strengthen my interest in the narratives of time through making, I constantly find ways to build up and decompose clay materials to show the impact of time. My studio is dusty with silt and clays from the past as much as with glazes of the present, and from time to time I have been a contributor of the fine dust that creeps everywhere in a studio practice that is committed to reduction. The surface of my reference group and heroes of art and design contains a gritty patina, as all who work with material, whether new or old, cannot avoid the residue of an immediate past that is written in the material, the scars of use, and all of the accoutrements of a life spent with hand and heart in relationship with the materials and tools we call upon to make visions.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I make primarily sculptural vessels and objects that exist in the social space that most people occupy. They can rest on shelves and in cupboards, but it’s the behavior of the body that creates their primary existence in my work.
        </p>
        <p>
        My driving is that I'm trying to understand the somatic nature of creating and the utility of that experience in my life; how it affects the way I walk around and interact with other people. The physical sensation of doing some-thing is something we all do, but the object that gets made is a product you can hold in your hand. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Wheth-er the works are cups, bowls, vessels with lids or handles or made out of wood, it’s still a physical sensation to hold these things in your hand, pick them up and hold onto them. So I make these things to distort the experiences people have when they hold something in their hand and hold onto it for a prolonged period of time. I distort those experiences, and I distort the objects that people hold onto, because I don't find normal everyday use-ful anymore. I feel that it's an opportunity to break some of the normalcy and use-fulness patterns of objects and come up with other ways of holding things that people might consider.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Prior to focusing entirely on my training and development as a blacksmith, I worked as a director, potter and visual artist. Now most of my own artwork has evolved out of the clay fields where I located myself, taking questions about the nature of clay and the methods of testing. Objects are made to reward beautiful symmetries in rows of bellies and coils; they invite natural straight lines into objects that nearly always take curves. My thorough investigation of wire also allowed me the freedom to design emotionally. My raised non-functional barbells and rings recall the protective enclosure of bridges at night. Other wire pieces named for markings on golf courses and tennis courts include surfaces with details mimicking the clean patterns of ball-strips. Swinging back and forth; objects flirt with tension, readying to break. The invitation to take (as the objects themselves take) the long elegant arcs of circular swings, more common in recreational fields than clay ones, will leave the viewer while contemplating the means by which something sturdy might exist in a state of exuberant openness. This fragile suggestion is further emanated from minimal gestures just under the surface, and from the fractured, inorganic planes of glazes.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Anticipation is a lean in the flesh, warm hand on cool tile, an eye on a wet bowl, hoping that moment the warm glaze hits the wood fired clay, or the drips begin their downward fall… these never failed epiphanies are the reward of a day’s work. This is where the art emerges.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        While potters may possibly choose to exhibit the series of their choice, I like to exhibit all of my current and past work in a continuous narrative of my time in the studio, balancing the desired social space of a home with that of a gallery.. Language in the studio for me is also an exercise that begins with the clay and fire. It is an investigation of the language of clay in terms of its expressive possibility. Identity is a very present notion as well. My work explores all senses of the male and female archetypes in order to include them in the narrative of contemporary pottery, expanding the definition of what pottery is in relation to art and activity. I am interested in the fact that our inner selves are often in conflict with what we do and say publicly in relation to ideas such as the homemaker/career, the male and female roles, and societal expectations. I attempt to address these concerns in art and photographs that range through time. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        In the MA student studio, we work within The Earth is a Factory School. The phrase was coined by my professor Paul Soldner, maker of large scale earthenware assemblage, incorporating elements from the wilderness where, at the time, UCLA Extension was situated in the foothills. After moving to Hampton, WA, The Earth is a Factory School has expanded to include the Coast Salish people. Their world relies on water for life, and provides a window for organic investigation of process and time. 
        </p>
        <p>
        In recent work, observation has led to relationships with sources that surpass "interiors" observed in mass production and manufacturing methods. Observation outside of one's own perceptions produces valuable data in both imagination and process. The material world is an open book for exploration of relationships with clay, nature, traditional craft, and methods of making. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Characterized as life-size, nature-mimicry, and abstracted, I assert that my flat-woven baskets are earthenware vessels that offer an organic language of self-identity. Streams, creeks, rivers, springs, beaches, tide pools, shores, and mudflats are frequent destinations along with land-based fieldwork
        The frameworks used to support two-dimensional wall work are fabricated of black willow. 
        AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE MEANING OF POTTERY IN CONTEMPORARY LIFE
        The importance of clay in cultures everywhere is vital.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I like the idea of developing a lexicon of forms built up like archaeological excavations, and then chipping away at the underside of the vessels, revealing something of how the vessel was constructed, and how the forms inhabit the space of the vessel. I then overburden the top of the vessel with additional planes of texture. This occurs because I believe it is important to create vessels that are a hybrid of the familiar and the uncanny and the familiar should not predominate.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I'm driven to make these welded oxidizations as a response to grief and loss in my life. Currently, I work in an electric kiln with a very intimate yet volatile process. I am tethered to these otherworldly combinations of the abstracted. The work draws huge amounts of transcendent heat while shielding me from it. I work with a skilled balance of self-consciousness and rigor. I want to put into the work some abstracted memory of death and resurrection, to deploy it as a talisman of how rich and disturbing a life can be.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        "My art is a journey into this world and this world's future. The theme of my work is light and shadow, hope and doubt. I seek to strengthen the human condition through my work and the emotions with which it is felt. As with our lives, little that I make can be defined into one way, and I like it that way. I want living viewers to question what they are thinking as they look at my work. I might like it if viewers miss things and ask the questions that I miss whenever I create something. I want pictures to provoke thinking rather than provide explanations. I hope that those who view my art are able to relate emotions and thoughts to things that they might read or have been taught or create themselves. I also like visual confusion in my art, as I don't like to be only understood, but rather be left in a state of continuous thought.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Context and belonging are key factors in the work studied or produced by any artist. The potter's wheel, the imprint of hands, the textures of tools, the crafting and creation of pottery, are mediums that revere many cultures; the culture of cuisine or houseware, utensil or sculpture. If we take a panorama of a household and stir in the element of history, then live bodies and emotions, currently-used items and then one response to an existing style or form would unfold at a larger scale on a global perspective. In my own journey of hands on and hands off interpreting statements and questions from a whirlwind of cultural influence, continues to be an opportunity to grow and change with every project I launch. This view, beyond that of other potters, has and always will be in my work, my creative being and an identity that marks me belonging to the world community. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        The stacks of thread spools, buttons, hinges and other found objects, imply a whole host of disjointed gestures acting independently of design. They are the outcomes of intuitive moves, rash decisions, and on-the-fly cohesions. They are numerous, disparate, and a smattering of things that define a particular space, but are otherwise thought of, only during the act of creating the art. 
        </p>
        <p>
        What began long ago as a ten-year mark to reflect and signify a point of contemplation, quickly morphed into a twenty-year mark. Each year approaching and passing, proved to be a complex melange of texture, simplicity and complexity. Each year was and is simultaneously a reflection of the past 20 years, as well as an omen to the 20 years that will be. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Beautiful patterns and shades of color that arrive from the inherent energy in any given color formed from a juxtaposition of off-the-shelf and prepared paints create works that stand alone and unexpected, with a sense of momentary flight as they enjoy space within the maze of time.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I love to explore how pottery connects with people; while the tangible strength of the material is mesmerizing to me, I find the resilience of aesthetic form and the versatility of the maker to be the compelling factors of human relationship. I explore the transformative nature of ceramics by playing with multiple forms of pottery practice. The tactile manipulation inherent to throwing, handcrafting, slab construction, and traditional coiling, are evidenced in my work alongside a new discipline showcasing stoneware clay-on-clay construction with hybrid stoneware-terra cotta glazing and wood smoke through traditional shino and kuro shino glazing.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Constantly aiming to reinvent myself and my work, I combine the potter’s individual physical and hand skills with inchoate subterranean forces and processes perceived through time, thoughts, memory and tell tenuous personal symbols of emotional response to my immediate experiences. Beneath microscopic fingerprints lies the story of my life and the life of my context, ultimately revealing a story of self and identity. My textile practice offers a freedom associated with an individual’s personal expression, without the constraints of functional utility. Conversely, my pottery expresses relationships between an individual’s want and need states, the pleasure derived from form and texture, the complexity of climate, and the restraints placed on form and function by nature’s forces. Hence, my work represents a maximalist point of view; from a Minimalist’s perspective to an Individualist’s point of view to a statement beyond discipline, process and production.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I draw inspiration from daily life, both my own and other's; contemplations of the natural sciences; the imagined "condition" of objects; myths, stories and folk tales; my history reading and research in art and my investigation into the geology and physical science within my home region. I am grateful for my archaeologist father. By investing history, time, excavation, and care into the acquisition of our own particular collection of artifacts, I find in the narrative of old artisans and the elusive tools they employed, a host of metaphors for the way I work now. I use the ordinary, the gash, the shiny, and the mundane in my work. I am fascinated by slop, fog, burl, fawn offshots, and the diversity of gases – I call my methods Methodology In Glaze and Creation Vessels.
        </p>
        <p>
        One summer I noticed how the glaze I most had a hard time fusing, a transparent frit, held glaze on the undersides of tea cups where as a transparent engobe, it scorched like a crop circle. Abstracting the implied dusted surface of a cake and the massive weight of ash, I am always looking for and grasping for this distinction. Reflecting the energy invested its making back into it and the world - a literalization of our deep connection with the natural sciences and human events - this backflow or "scratchback" puts a personal mark on a pot. I live on a rural road in Southern New Hampshire, a place where farmers still follow the patterns of the Moon and weathervanes align; I am inspired by watching the cycles of the night sky, by seasonal changes, by my community of friends, new and old, and by geological anomalies right here at my fingertips. This all spins up my own stories, which I speak and lay down traces of like a comet over a celestial map. My passion is for this dialogue of spinning a body to ice: to make it in a moment, fill it with a year's evening work, and have it last a lifetime.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Porcelain: technically very pure, translucent and nutrientless, only man-made material to successfully imitate natural (quartz) crystal in clarity and brilliance. It freezes liquid bones, dissolved minerals from fire to make glaze fawn thin, veins, clear in lime, melding smoke to body in porcelain hearth. Requires highly refined mineral parts:
        </p>
        <p>
        Curiously harmonious mixture of a more nascent fauna than mineral, organic earthy (like filled bark, fibrous) porcelain fossilized aura, alchemical process of fire, water --inherent, architectural, static process, waiting for nature in/of glaze to ransack clay casing clots upon glaze rests. Takes time, skilled workers to master carefully controlled manipulation of this flesh and bone --extends life by beauty of imperfections, one from dust accepting of entropy/addiction to beauty of impermanent tools. Porcelain’s matter broken by distortions, scars, rings, flu resist glazes spiral earth limbic calcite, lava scape in/unaware endless water movement, eternal sprawl, crystalline dreaming, intentional mark waver/trembles air/porcelain less joint unbroken criticality delicacy /gossamer haze/smoke/water---constant accidental constant combustion controlled incomplete magical inner body exposed shape/decorous manners/morals in peril make and use small daily ceremonies until all are ‘did then’s’ ransacked bones into lacy/gossamer minuscule. --Kate Rushton
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        There is growth, and maintenance, of life and death in the make of this body of work. Constructed, and destroyed. Organics, and non-organics. Woven, and webbed. Stoic. Sculptural, and slump. Dazzling, and ash. Glassiness, and flame, blinding, beguiling. Soft, and hard. Must have form. Apply outside forms. Bring inside forms. Seal. And crack open. Primary and secondary forms. Edges. Soft edges. Bold edges. Polished. And un-polish. Stains. Impact. Saturations. Deprivation. Broaden borders. Strict guards. Envelopes. Rootling and Treeing. Seeking. To plant. Root, and blossom. Set surface. And lace it, insulating inside. Crust. P&B. With overtones. Lightness. Air of. Between breaths. Breath into it. Breathe out of it. W/pressure. And hollowness. Smells, and smells. Bonded, and un-bonded connections. Alive. Excitement of. Of. Unveilings. Second chances. To make again. And again. With material. Skeletal. That requires. That needs. That is. Aware. And conscious. Welcome to. Belly of. And muscle of. My. Skegg & Jackson.
        Look up over handle. Of cup. Ask: What fathom. Basket do I live in?
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Contemporary ceramics have been strongly influenced by eastern philosophies and the principles of Zen Buddhism and Taoism. They focus on reduction in form and design, especially in the area of decoration, striving for unity with the simple and the elemental in a reduction to the absolute. Although I do not practice reductionism, these philosophies provide mental direction toward what has become my main interest, the direct connection between the vessel as living space and the vessel as vessel. These vessels are intended to be natural extensions of everyday life, for each person to live and grow in, therefore, the form and function must remain consistent and matured.
        </p>
        <p>
        In my vessels, the norm is to wear over time. While the body of the vessel could be convoluted into the traditional form of western ceramics the surface and the glaze, are different. The earliest surface application in one of my vessels mimics a pattern of randomness. This is an intentional presentation of frosting. Over time, the frosting disappears and the surface matures. It breaks down from a flat surface into a more textured form presenting character and introspection. Glaze settling between surface and clay also creates the same type of uneven textured surface. As in life, the vases are not perfect and therefore must mature. This process keeps the vessel and myself interested visually over time. The aged surface is also broken by techniques such as piercing and carving. Both penetrate the thick and tough surface. These scars are another part of life that add to the surface maturity and visually adds another quality to the vessel. Scrimshaw and zinc pedal paint are also ways to modify the surface. These "happy accidents" create more interest to the surface and create a more sensual space.
        </p>
        <p>
        Contradicting the east Asia philosophy of the plain and simple, I found by carving the surface they are the opposite. They are better, more interesting and alive. The organic shapes are a contrast to structured forms and a juxtaposition of casual to fine. As someone who enjoys the mystery of life and the boisterous stages of development, I want my vessels to convey that enthusiasm while still being fashionable. Vessels that have matured, cracked and had the surface beat up, now become charming. They are even more alive. The contrast of visual and structural severity, contemporary and historical, pretension and folkloric, allows for another simultaneous consideration. This structure and surface contrast helps to show how this space was built upon small ideas, hope and chance, all contributing to the building of this interesting outcome.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I create surfaces for contemplation. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Depositions, gray and black shades melt, dissolve and form pools. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Water is spilled into these surfaces, testing the strength of agate’s smooth surface. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Shattering and shifting push and pull these surfaces into saturated tension. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Planar tension wedges inward: pushing boundaries of surface and shape. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Saturating the vessel substance, the body of the vessel. 
        </p>
        <p>
        The natural impulse is to press against the surface, to embed within the form.
        </p>
        <p>
        Pressing in a confined space.
        </p>
        <p>
        Substance over saturated. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Soaking already wet. 
        </p>
        <p>
        The vessel has shifted planes causing a rupture in its structural integrity.
        </p>
        <p>
        Fractured into many parts like the potato. 
        </p>
        <p>
        When fire bites and pulls to explode these parts into freedom.
        </p>
        <p>
        Vessel of failure.
        </p>
        <p>
        </p>
        <p>
        Like the potato. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Burning. 
        </p>
        <p>
        This sculpture is ready to return to the composting.
        </p>
        <p>
        The rebirth of ceramic art.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Autumn's Vessel is a rustic, utilitarian form composed of multiple pieces ceramic. Specifically, it is a prehistoric and ancient shape for the storage or gathering of food or life providing sustenance, and a weight for precious commodities.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I find elegance though paradox, roughness or contrast in the contrasts. 
        My work expresses the cultural concepts of inner and outer, up and down, with a focus on the interdependence of form and surface to create an aesthetic contact with the viewer. 
        My hope is to humanize this interdependence, lending to understanding through the mirroring of expression. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Contemporary ceramics
        </p>
        <p>
        is polychrome, critical
        </p>
        <p>
        and reflective of our global
        </p>
