        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        When I walk, I draw. Drawing in the landscape is a personal and meditative act that extends the composition of the whole and offers a starting point for paint application upon returning to the studio. The environment triggers an emotional response and references the day’s experiences. The landscape observes our evolving culture while remaining consistent. The drawings are representations of feeling and experience, the maps, charts, and notes made of effects rather than details. Consistency of basic line, color and drawing structure allow digression into visual motifs that explore ideas and formal design. Visual rhythms, compression, division, contrast and transition provoke emotional responses and evoke memories and stories. Space discovery, surface, hue, value and patterns are used as vehicles to express meaning. An image is inevitably woven into the drawing that exposes a state of the mind. The mind of the artist remains in the process and more importantly within the final compositions. These works are studies of observances and connections that explore the essence of humanity through basic emotions, the invisible and the common. A lasting breath envisions momentary fusion on a journey that transcends time and space...to her!
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Glaze defines surface color to the final drying stages of clay bodies, while clay itself remains the principal body manifesting form. Each new body signifies a language of clay where linearity may be broken, slashes and drags of clay gestures temper turbulent steel-toned surface information, while fired sand applications push the fray of the discussion beyond the vessel.
        </p>
        <p>
        Awareness of glaze chemical makeup along with color and texture possibilities builds a dialog between glazed surfaces and vessels formed from the interpreted and translated poetry of clay at the moment. These conversations encourage nuanced decorative decisions that emerge from varied methods of working with paint and glaze, while refined printing methods of stencils and slips enhance the dialogue. Through combinations of slip, glaze and paint layer upon layer of surface information creates a unified installation of decisions and gestures interpreted by hand.
        </p>
        <p>
        Side-by-side or staggered rows of clay and glaze questions the ideation of surface. Alternatingly droplet shaped clusters of clay and condensed paste sequences expose sublime micro textures. These surface gradients push and pull upon each other, section to section and bowl to bowl, using color and texture to sculpt excess. The poem in clay stays close to the earth, feeding off soil, minerals, water and sun. A new body offers a momentary resting place, before hurrying along it’s way for another material form to fill. 
        Equally, when careless touch, pavers and trowels, brushes and brayers, stencils and prints, all busy together on a surface push and pull too close to each other. Harmony arrives in tactile curiosity and the curve of a vessel reveals itself. Demur to the moment and a tactile excitement awaits the hand to smuggle into the world. 
        </p>
        <p>
        My touch lands materials on surfaces and in this series it must remain. Process of layering and slivering is encouraged from the near liquid to the dry slurry. 
        The opening and closing of vessels creates new opportunities for interactions of glaze and clay. Continuing to build and accumulating glaze surface, slipped surfaces assume a new light awakened to spatial explorations. 
        </p>
        <p>
        Pattern is appreciated but openly controlled and manipulated. Resisting restraint, the hand and mind find happiness in the slip across a glaze and the resulting tone of the space created by the touch, and is happy enough not to know which came first. 
        Strangely, the accidental coincidence emerges and is stronger for it’s serendipitous arrival, and serves notice to a world whose talkative gestures and quiet whispers are signs of a common language.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        The program is suggested through the material, limiting to two bodies, two different clay bodies similar with transitional material includes dish and slip, a translucency and an opalescence. The individual entry components are similar in scale, necessitating each to engage the other. The silhouettes are individuated through a series of volumes. The smokiness of the upper smoke flap and broad overhanging roof are balanced against the vertical industrial look of the pipes at the platform seating area. The counter of the part of the tower seen at the entry end of the building is the root of the interlocking delicate reeds which “grow” out into the main area. Each vein on these is accentuated, the skin becomes thinner, and the vein branch wider as they develop outwards to the exterior walls at the canopied seating level in the large area.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Ceramics and painting have been grouped before as well as still are, particularly as the rise of ceramic painting occurred simultaneously with the rise of modernism. Although each discipline is born from fundamentally different traditions, their marriage seems logical. Both involve pushing two-dimensional material into complicated three-dimensional forms. And the surface is an operative feature in both media, although it functions more like a crucial interface where interactions between material and physical context take shape.
        </p>
        <p>
        However, there are significant differences. While painting is fluid, spontaneous, and one of the last remaining free creative powers available to mankind, ceramics is mechanical, systematic, and bound by materials and techniques that seem scarcely spontaneous and prone to the course of convention.
        I have been working with the metaphor of the painting within the constraints of the ceramic medium, throwing down and building up multiple colored pinch pots. Occasional brushes of slip, layer of glaze, and braiser flash have allowed more painting creative directions and results the way using transparent watercolor transitions on paper or wood might, a glaze wash allowing more paint decisions, etc. The result has been throwing each paint color separately, one by one, and allowing each throw to fire. After about three firings, the colors normally reveal themselves in a triadic set of ragged interplays between cool form, muted undulation, and screaming dense black/white and the associated set of colors, evolving over time. This is a discovery process. The whole interval from initial matching of each of the colors, to the final revelation of the set of colors, is roughly the same length of time as I would devote to making one large color field painting in oil. The throw, fire, lever, open up, throw, more fire, more clay, open up, more clay, and on and on for several centimeters, could last a whole day. Then you focus and see it and work it through to a satisfying end.
        </p>
        <p>
        Now how to get people to attack, manufacture, glaze fire, polish, glaze, kiln fire, to 14 highly technical steps, three days, thousands of hours, for 35 dollars a vase using the throw and fire method? The technical issues are staggering at that level of financial commitment to labor. 
        Artists are beginning to embrace this approach that comes from the attitude of “making” rather “painting.” And, a new series of challenges and discoveries in making is stimulated through the trade-off of limitations of the thrown form itself. I get tremendous pleasure form this approach. Its difficult. I envy the casual approach and choice of material, brush type, and variety of materials that oil painters have available. However, not only is there wonderfully subversive appeal to the stripping away of contemporary glaze culture, but it opens a range of throwing and altering that is unique in ceramics and a source of endless fascination.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Ceramics and painting are analogous in a respect in that they follow models - rules that govern the construction of their subjects. Their procedures are similar in the way that one begins with an idea primary or an element, and continues to build from there. One knows they have finished a painting when it feels finished. However, they are radically different in the sense that one is purely visual in its cues, while the other has both visual and functional characteristics. The paradox lies in how to convert this from a useful piece to a form that is pleasing to the eye, or that flourishes from its inextricable ties with function. I want to push the limits in which I push the roles that pottery plays in our lives. I feel it is my duty to communicate the abilities of this fleeting form to provide our food, drink, and enjoyment for us to remember the agency it plays in our lives. I would like to punish the pot with the same prestige and hardness as painting, but still end up with something that is socially legible. A Bετος is a pot piece that negates its practical use and at the same time intends to pretend it is a useful object. Its form is a prop to remember to visit what is fleeting.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        "I created pots as an act with these gestures.
        </p>
        <p>
        I will create again with these intentions.
        </p>
        <p>
        I molded it to bring forth what was dormant. 
        </p>
        <p>
        My hands sculpted it because there was room."
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        My fascination with ceramic vessels started when I was in college, making sculptural pots without feet and bases. After digging around at flea markets, yard sales, antiques shops, and my own grandma's stuff (who loved pottery FROM there to China) I turned an early passion into a love. I now find it impossible to let a year pass without making at least one pot. You can't believe how much you can learn from a piece of clay. I particularly find inspiration from ancient forms of ceramics - from Chinese rice bowls to Hopi Pueblo to Mayan. The craft of ceramics has long been about storytelling, so my pots reflect these stories. I love how a break in the surface tells the hero's journey of a story in a pot. It is a history of acquisition and use as well as a projection of one's reasons.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I look for my ideas in things that live within not far from us. Everything here is beautiful. I look to country life where we are. Beans are in the fields have been in the evening and morning. A bubbling brook across the road. The nest by the china barn and the china barn door planted with daylilies. There is no need for of far flung black and white and shadows of gray. My world is fluorescent and full-color 3D, flora and fauna. As I spend most of my time here I to take away the worries and to support rural life.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I view ceramics and painting as two sides of the same media. Both have innate capabilities of symbolization and representation. Glazed ceramics have traditionally functioned as more decorative than clay. On the other side of painting, the medium will unite with the information of painting. The symbol form an interesting intermediate stage between two major forms of communication, glazing ceramics. I use the clay and glazes not only to symbolize mark-making, but also to charge them with the secret breath and nub of imagination. 
        </p>
        <p>
        My clay starts with strong taste of dirt. In order to interact with the natural ceramic materials, instead of fighting, I adapt to the ceramic materials. For clay, I search archaeological brushes, dung mud, and nothing is too dirty. I have to treat these “dirty” things for designing cups and jars. The base of most of my works is traditional casting process from natural clay either from South China clay or North china clay.
        </p>
        <p>
        The main reason for applying glazes is that my intentions are not in depicting the images, landscapes or flowers, I want to achieve my own aesthetic intention and initiate my imagination. Glazes are the final layer of work to symbolize the mark-making of clay. There is an evolution: first the surface of the clay, that's why “Only Clay can hold my breath full of silence”; second glaze poured on the clay is the color membrane of the hard surface. And third is painting. I paint each piece when dry after the glaze set, has been picked up the pigment from the floor of inspiration to the pieces and here vessels are separated from the real life. They are symbolic and are associated with contemporary living. Them are about information, communicative, rather than containers or forms.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        When the unexpected and absurd join the expected, each reveals the comically absurd, and I’m able to transfer it onto the ceramic form. The inherent plasticness of clay becomes my favorite tool for provoking the bodily to reenact awkward life through the expressive power of clay, and the ceramic form itself becomes imbued with complex humor. Unmasking the core of each form exposes a bumbling spirit in clay — humor. I hope to expose a new ingenious relationship between object form and bodily predicament, human and air. In all it is to overthrow the prescriptive, a serious and pedantic attitude, to reform the studious evolution of ceramic forms, and to create something playful with a dash of “everything or nothing” — a simple and joyous stance that goes against the grain of etiquette, tradition, and predictability. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        By mood and feel, I am very attracted to the influences of the cultures and people I encounter in my travels. They become a part of me for the time that I am there. I can’t wait to come home to make them a part of my imagined world. Working with clay has elements of slowness and time to accompany the revealing question, “How do I say what I believe?” I use shape to communicate harmonizing a tricky relationship between the ceramic object and human scale. The surface is another place a conversation may occur. In my case the appearance of easy command may belie multiple failed attempts and many happy accidents.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Though a variety of materials have been utilized throughout the history of ceramic sculpture, clay has proven to be durable yet malleable enough to be flexible to the needs of the artist. Redundancies found in nature such as rock, wood and grasses form the basis for almost all sculptural works. Layers upon layers of carved and thinned deep lines and grooves are added to the surface gives sculptures an illusion of depth and texture that becomes important when having the piece in stark contrast to a wall or on its own. Color is usually added in small controlled doses and always in a way to compliment the overall composition. Pieces are fired in an out door clamshell kiln. Glazes and slips are tested on tiles to ensure commitment to scale, form and function. Pottery is the heart of what I produce so it represents the majority of my work. My figurative work attempts to capture the depth and tactile sensitivity of my pottery by re-creating the curves and lines applied to my ceramic animals with clay collage on found boards.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Pottery is a tangible representation of memory that represents both personal lives and public histories. My core artistic inquiry is seeking identity through memory and community through my artwork. As a child of Vietnamese immigrant parents, the act of making art was for me the process of carving our stories into the memories, both painful and poignant, of my family’s journey into understanding what it is to be American. Art making has allowed me to understand the relationship between my sundering individualistic American consciousness and my collective as an integrated American culture. My works often reflect imagery and artifacts of refugee camps, and testify through their participation in public spaces the disconnect between our cultural values and actual conditions for immigrants. In tandem with critical debates about the current state of American identity and values, I am also interested in using the visual language of ceramics to express my search for personal identity. Utilizing ceramic ancestry accordions as symbols of my female-to-male transition from Miwa to Edwin Fennell made and included in my work seeks to be a body of work that raises awareness of representation of gender identity through material indexical representation.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Rowan Donovan combines an interest in natural sciences, detail oriented design, and an intuitive appreciation of natural form driven by vivid organic color. My earthen depressions are an exploration into the principles of abstraction, rather than the objects themselves. The act of collection is not so much a part of the process as it is the visualization. Working with transparent and translucent glazes is atypical of the ceramic process by which I’m interested in a particular sort of echo that only becomes clear by some small amount of distance. Continuing to look at the work and continue to remember is a necessary part of this work. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I work with historically ceramic formats (throwing, handbuilding, and slabbuilding) and surfaces (slips- underglazes on semi-transparent terracottas, and ceramic-asbociated uses of colors, textures, and surfaces) rejecting a thematic approach to an actual and engaging ceramics studio practice; I make ceramic compositions with a meditative dimension that integrates automonumentic visions from years of engagement with grand texts, myth, oral stories and dreams. 
        In recent years, I have explored elements of glazes, slips, under-glazes and specific on-glazes, searches for the limits of ceramic mediums and surfaces, and consideration of the ceramic as contemporary sculpture expand my notions of ceramic materiality. Extended from the notion of ceramic-as-decoration, I integrate this practice with a surface/object systemic language. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        My ceramics are primarily hand-built, and feature complex layering of slips and underglazes, as well as natural materials and glazes. Through brush work, layering of organic materials and slips, additions of hand-formed interior “sculptures” made from local native clay, and hand-placed glazes either to expose layerings, depths, and voluptuous curves or tones, I want to convey the thrill of the process that is a big part of what I find exciting about making pots. More than wanting to create celebrations over a cup of tea or inspiring a meal, my pots are about a storytelling that goes beyond their functionality to communicate the narrative of my experiences from the places I’ve travelled and the studio I inhabit. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        “Ideas are all well and good, but the question remains whether they will translate the same way in three dimensions. Are these ideas strong enough to survive the translation? The physicality of it all is what intrigues and motivates me. I’m forever in a state of investigating and dissecting. Or, rather, being incapable of internalizing a concept and grasping it all as a whole so I spend cheap prices on the pleasure of eroding materials. That is the secret, to keep it simple. This concept is something I still fight with almost daily. Simplicity can be an elusive thing in this world of details. My work reflects on how a simple idea can inform so many concepts and thoughts. Through this I am constantly amazed by the potential of the things around me.”
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        The pots I make are liberated from preordained forms and functions, accidental, altered and altered again as they change materially and psychologically throughout their life spans, behaving like viscous, misunderstood teenagers. They resist categorization according to time, place or circumstance, symbols on their surface and casting vary at once, some small stories animate their surface. Worn by the hand those seeds will flourish; sutured to their disparate origins, continually evolving to self-discover.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Obviously my triffid-shaped pots are humorous and satirical, frequently depicting facial expressions, animals or human beings. These mixed feelings stem from the fact that ceramic is a nice material to work and on the other hand there is the feeling that it is a bit cheap or old-fashioned. So, for me, the pinch pots are also not too high-class. As a reaction, I produce those exaggeratedly nice and refined pinch pots. They may be comical as well, but have something in common with the refined double flowers of former times.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        My pots are narratives of contradiction: furniture seems to careen off the wall and, at the same time, lean into a hug. Plates seem to hover an inch from the table. Pots are insistent and demanding, and yet gentle in how they inhabit our lives and table settings.
        Their stories involve searching. Not for truth, nor answers, but for lines of dialogue and a deeper sense of our common ground. My aims are to create tools for the discovery of beginning and ending and the play between the concepts.
        Custom design or place setting for friends.
        Work that I have created specifically for company and community in my studios or rented studios, never for sale.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I make pots in diverse scales. I like detail and scale relationships that challenge an audience and seem puzzling in their arrangement. I find the contradictory ideas of fresh yet intricate, familiar yet obscure, alien yet safe in three dimensional form irresistible. My work is narrative and actions are contained by the space boundaries you find on a tabletop. Primarily my stories deal with home, identity, and culture, friendships and relationships. I gained the confidence to take this in another direction after class by leaving behind the confines of the figurative and being confident to move my work in any direction I wish.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        In general I like to carve thick and build up and sand molds and build up multiple layers of color then carve down through all the layers to around a thousand grit then use many colors and pounce all the legs and handles. My biggest struggle is finding a way to make my wood-fired pots presentable. Their size leaves me with choices of making them more decoration like or having to create that dramatic band around the foot that drives a conversation and makes them decoration like. 
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        I use clay as a paintbrush and wood-fire as a paint-dryer. I create fluid compositions conjuring images of space travel, sci-fi comic book influences, and futuristic visions of space. My pots are treated as they are manufactured. Not like an item of utility but rather like a culturally important glimpse of human creativity. Each piece contains origins and marks of its own specific surface finish story.
        At a point in the continuum between corrective and compressive repair, the surface turns into a seductive substrate of possible invention. The molded and cut forms abound in accidents and unintended visual reactions, becoming meshed into a significant surface event that offers unexpected surprises.
        Surcharging via structural collapse results in a visibly dramatic demarcation between an initially recognizable form and its final resolution. The glaze creates fluidic surfaces animating above and below its surface plane. Surfaces against colors suggest illusions, leading to illusive infinity. Benday rhythms are a compulsive drug. Treatment through function is fundamental. The visual imagination of possibilities keeps molten clay in motion.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Counteracting traditional European design principles, I attempt an open inquiry to deliciously formless shapes by playfully reducing domestic and food service vessels to new levels of functionality, minimalistic elegance and conceptual implications.
        </p>
        <h4 class="title is-4">Artist Statement</h4>
        <p>
        Using a minimalist approach and through a series of modifications and critical thinking, I investigate how ceramic form can acquire multiple and articulated functions.  My approach to the work undermines a historical conventionality and instead cultivates mindful connections to ancient cultures and a balance between cognition, connection and action.  I strip each piece down to its bare bones, reflecting a value and criticality to the historical significance and physicality of ceramic form.
        </p>
